Figure 6. Roles of Siglec15 in predicting immune phenotypes in the XiangYing cohort. (C) Correlations between Siglec15 and the steps of the cancer immunity cycle. (D) Correlations between Siglec15 and the enrichment scores of immunotherapy-predicted pathways.

  • CD
  • Siglec15P value

Plot Analysis

  • Use a heatmap to display the autocorrelation analysis results of the pathways.
  • The two heatmaps, C and D, respectively show the correlation analysis results of two types of pathways, placed together for easy comparison.
  • Use lines to show the correlation between Siglec15 and each specific pathway of the two types. Solid lines represent positive correlation, dashed lines represent negative correlation, and color represents the P-value.

| Application Scenario

CD1Siglec15CSiglec15DCD

111

CDeasy_input*

Display correlation analysis results, many-to-many (C heatmap, D heatmap), one-to-many (Siglec15 connections with C, Siglec15 connections with D), two-group comparison (C and D plotted together).

The example shows correlations between 1 gene and multiple pathways, which can be replaced with correlations between 1 gene and multiple genes, or 1 pathway and multiple genes, etc., for flexible application.

If there is only one group, its a separate C or D; if there are two groups, combine them like a butterfly as in the example; if there are more groups, apply the same easy_input* files, create multiple plots, and combine them according to your aesthetic preferences.

# gmtpathifier
# Read gmt file as list format to meet pathifier input requirements

gmt2list <- function(annofile){
  if (!file.exists(annofile)) {
    stop("There is no such gmt file.")
  }
  
  if (tools::file_ext(annofile) == "xz") {
    annofile <- xzfile(annofile)
    x <- scan(annofile, what="", sep="\n", quiet=TRUE)
    close(annofile)
  } else if (tools::file_ext(annofile) == "gmt") {
    x <- scan(annofile, what="", sep="\n", quiet=TRUE)
  } else {
    stop ("Only gmt and gmt.xz are accepted for gmt2list")
  }
  
  y <- strsplit(x, "\t")
  names(y) <- sapply(y, `[[`, 1)
  
  annoList <- lapply(y, `[`, c(-1,-2))
  return(annoList)
}

If your data is already formatted as easy_input_*.txt, you can directly proceed to Start Plotting.

Below, using gene expression matrix and pathway-gene information, calculate the enrichment scores for each pathway (can be understood as pathway expression matrix).

  • tcga_blca_fpkm.txt: Gene expression matrix.
  • Pathway gene information: The example paper organized two types of pathways based on literature, other pathways can follow this format:
    • bladder cancer signature.txt: bladder cancer-related signatures, with one pathway per row, first column as pathway name (Signature), second column as genes (Genes). Used for plotting (C) Correlations between Siglec15 and the steps of the cancer immunity cycle. Derived from Table S9.xlsx of the example paper, Bladder cancer signatures, taking Signature and Genes columns. Organized by the example paper authors from this article: Mariathasan S, Turley SJ, Nickles D, Castiglioni A, Yuen K, Wang Y, et al.TGF attenuates tumour response to PD-L1 blockade by contributing to exclusion of T cells. Nature. 2018; 554: 544-8.
    • immunotherapy predicted pathways.txt: therapeutic signatures, used for plotting (D) Correlations between Siglec15 and the enrichment scores of immunotherapy-predicted pathways. Organized from Table S9.xlsx of the example paper, Therapeutic predicted pathways, selecting Pathways with Description as Anticancer_immunotherapy and their corresponding Genes. Can be directly used in your own article, remember to cite the example paper

A set of gene signatures positively correlated with the clinical response of an anti-PD-L1 agent (atezolizumab) in BLCA were collected from Mariathasans study [27]. Twelve bladder cancer signatures that are specific to different molecular subtypes were collected from the study performed by the Bladder Cancer Molecular Taxonomy Group [19]. We also collected other therapeutic signatures, including oncogenic pathways that could shape a non-inflamed TME, targeted therapy-associated gene signatures, and gene signatures predicting radiotherapy responses (Table S9).

# load TCGA-BLCA FPKM
expr <- read.table("tcga_blca_fpkm.txt",sep = "\t",row.names = 1,check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F,header = T)
tumsam <- colnames(expr)[substr(colnames(expr),11,13) == "01A"] # 
# load immunotherapy-predicted pathways
immPath <- read.table("immunotherapy predicted pathways.txt",sep = "\t",row.names = 1,check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F,header = T)
immPath.list <- list()
for (i in rownames(immPath)) {
  tmp <- immPath[i,"Genes"]
  tmp <- toupper(unlist(strsplit(tmp,", ",fixed = T)))
  tmp <- gsub(" ","",tmp)
  immPath.list[[i]] <- tmp
}

# load bladder cancer related signatures
blcaPath <- read.table("bladder cancer signature.txt",sep = "\t",row.names = 1,check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F,header = T)
blcaPath.list <- list()
for (i in rownames(blcaPath)) {
  tmp <- blcaPath[i,"Genes"]
  tmp <- toupper(unlist(strsplit(tmp,", ",fixed = T)))
  tmp <- gsub(" ","",tmp)
  blcaPath.list[[i]] <- tmp
}

# immunotherapy-predicted pathways
# Calculate enrichment scores for immunotherapy-predicted pathways
immPath.param <- GSVA::ssgseaParam(
  as.matrix(log2(expr[,tumsam] + 1)),
  immPath.list
)
immPath.score <- GSVA::gsva(immPath.param, verbose = FALSE)
## ! 694 genes with constant values throughout the samples
#  | Save to file for easy reuse
write.table(immPath.score, "easy_input_immPath.txt", sep = "\t", row.names = TRUE, col.names = NA, quote = FALSE)

msigdbgmtc5.all.v7.4.symbols.gmt

For your own data, you may want to extract pathways of interest and calculate their enrichment scores. You can download the gmt file c5.all.v7.4.symbols.gmt from msigdb, extract pathways of interest and their corresponding genes, and calculate enrichment scores.

# gmt | Extract pathways of interest from gmt file
# `METABOLISM` | For example, extract pathways containing `METABOLISM`
gset <- gmt2list("c5.all.v7.4.symbols.gmt") 

# data.table%like%METABOLISM
# Use data.table's %like% operator to extract pathways containing METABOLISM
gset.list <- gset[names(gset) %like% "METABOLISM"]

#   Check if gene set is empty
if (length(gset.list) == 0) {
  stop("No pathways found containing 'METABOLISM'. Please check your gmt file and filter criteria.")
}

cat("Found", length(gset.list), "pathways containing 'METABOLISM'\n")

#  | Calculate pathway enrichment scores
gset.score <- GSVA::gsva(
  expr = as.matrix(log2(expr[, tumsam] + 1)),
  gset.idx.list = gset.list,
  method = "ssgsea",
  verbose = FALSE,  #   Reduce output information
  parallel.sz = 1   #   Run single-threaded to avoid parallel issues
)

#  | Save to file
write.table(gset.score, "easy_input_gset.txt", sep = "\t", row.names = TRUE, col.names = NA, quote = FALSE)

cat("Pathway enrichment scores saved to 'easy_input_gset.txt'\n")

This plot uses -log10(p-value) to visualize significance levels, which is a standard practice in bioinformatics. Higher values indicate stronger significance:

  • Line colors are encoded based on -log10(p-value)
  • The legend displays both p-value ranges and corresponding -log10(p-value) ranges
  • Reference: https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/dyaeBr8tnJhxN-fuYjE-hQ
# "1""1"
# Load expression of a single gene, which is the "1" in "1-to-many"
siglec15 <- read.csv("easy_input_gene.csv", row.names = 1, check.names = F)

#  | Load first set of enrichment scores
immPath.score <- read.table("easy_input_immPath.txt", check.names = F)
# SIGLEC15 | Merge with target gene SIGLEC15 expression
immPath.score <- rbind.data.frame(immPath.score,
                                  siglec15)

| Loop to calculate correlations and plot

# Loop to calculate correlations and plot bottom left
immCorSiglec15 <- NULL
for (i in rownames(immPath.score)) {
  #   Ensure data is numeric
  x_data <- as.numeric(immPath.score[i,])
  y_data <- as.numeric(siglec15)

  cr <- cor.test(x_data, y_data, method = "pearson")
  immCorSiglec15 <- rbind.data.frame(immCorSiglec15,
                                     data.frame(gene = "Siglec15",
                                                path = i,
                                                r = cr$estimate,
                                                p = cr$p.value,
                                                stringsAsFactors = F),
                                     stringsAsFactors = F)
}
immCorSiglec15$sign <- ifelse(immCorSiglec15$r > 0,"pos","neg")
immCorSiglec15$absR <- abs(immCorSiglec15$r)
immCorSiglec15$rSeg <- as.character(cut(immCorSiglec15$absR,c(0,0.25,0.5,0.75,1),labels = c("0.25","0.50","0.75","1.00"),include.lowest = T))
immCorSiglec15$pSeg <- as.character(cut(-log10(immCorSiglec15$p),c(0,2,5,10,Inf),labels = c("ns (p0.01)","<0.01 (2-log10p<5)","<0.001 (5-log10p<10)","<1e-10 (-log10p10)"),include.lowest = T))
immCorSiglec15[nrow(immCorSiglec15),"pSeg"] <- "Not Applicable"

immCorSiglec15$rSeg <- factor(immCorSiglec15$rSeg, levels = c("0.25","0.50","0.75","1.00"))
immCorSiglec15$pSeg <- factor(immCorSiglec15$pSeg, levels = c("<1e-10 (-log10p10)","<0.001 (5-log10p<10)","<0.01 (2-log10p<5)","Not Applicable","ns (p0.01)"))
immCorSiglec15$sign <- factor(immCorSiglec15$sign, levels = c("pos","neg"))

p1 <- quickcor(t(immPath.score), 
         type = "lower",
         show.diag = TRUE) + 
  geom_colour() +
  add_link(df = immCorSiglec15, 
           mapping = aes(colour = pSeg, size = rSeg, linetype = sign),
           spec.key = "gene",
           env.key = "path",
           diag.label = FALSE) +
  scale_size_manual(values = c(0.5, 1, 1.5, 2)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#19A078","#DA6003","#7570B4","#E8288E","#65A818")) +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "#9483E1",mid = "white",high = "#E11953",midpoint=0) +
  remove_axis("x")
p1

ggsave(filename = "ggcor plot in bottom left.pdf", width = 10,height = 8)
